PERMIAN HIGHWAY PIPELINE LLC STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS FOR TRANSPORTATION SERVICE Article I. Introduction 1.1 PERMIAN HIGHWAY PIPELINE LLC ("Transporter"), a Delaware limited liability company, operates facilities in the state of Texas for the purchase, sale, and transportation of Gas. Transporter is an "intrastate pipeline" within the meaning of Section 2(16) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978 (as it may be amended, modified or supplemented from time to time, the "NGPA") and is subject to the original jurisdiction of the Railroad Commission of Texas pursuant to Tex. Rev. Civ. Stat. Ann. arts. 6050, et seq., and 1446(e) (Vernon Supp. 1994), as it may be amended, modified or supplemented from time to time. 1.2 Transporter is filing this Statement in accordance with Section 284.123(e) of the regulations of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") for the purpose of setting forth the general terms and operating conditions under which Transporter will provide Firm Transportation Service and Interruptible Transportation Service for qualified Shippers pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA, as implemented by Subpart C of Part 284 of the FERC's regulations ("Section 311"). 1.3 The rules and regulations of the FERC govern all services provided under Section 311. If any term or provision in the Transportation Agreement is inconsistent with these rules or regulations or this Statement, the rules, regulations and this Statement will control and the Transportation Agreement will be deemed modified accordingly. Article II. Definitions 2.1 "Adequate Assurance of Performance" has the meaning ascribed in Article XXI Creditworthiness of this Statement. 2.2 "Affiliate" means, in relation to any person, any entity controlled, directly or indirectly, by the person, any entity that controls, directly or indirectly, the person or any entity directly or indirectly under common control with the person For this purpose, "control" of any entity or person means ownership of at least ten percent (10%) of the voting power of the entity or person. 2.3 "Btu" means British Thermal Unit(s). 2.4 "Central Clock Time" means the local time, including changes for Daylight Savings Time, in the Houston, Texas metropolitan area. 2.5 "Commercially Free" unless otherwise governed by an express quantity allowance for any impurity, means Gas of marketable grade and quality that may contain foreign materials, but only in such amounts that do not render the gas unmerchantable by preventing the proper operation of gas transmission or measurement equipment (such as line, regulators, meters or similar type equipment). It is understood that Gas commercially free of foreign materials and objectionable liquids and/or solids may require processing and filtration for its particular intended use by Shipper and Shipper assumes all such risk. 2.6 "Cubic Foot" and "Cubic Feet" means the amount of Gas necessary to fill a cubic foot of space at Standard Temperature and Standard Pressure. 2.7 "Day" means a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time. 2.8 "Delivery Point(s)" means the point(s) at which Transporter delivers the Gas to Shipper. 2.9 "Electronic Flow Measurement" or "EFM" means a Gas flow computer and related transducers and analyzers located at a metering point which computes and records the volume and energy content of the Gas flowing through the meter. 2.10 "Equivalent Quantity" means that quantity of Gas which is thermally equivalent to the quantity of Gas delivered by Shipper to Transporter on any one (1) Day (less Estimated Mainline Fuel and Fixed Downstream Fuel, as applicable). 2.11 "Estimated Mainline Fuel" has the meaning ascribed in Article VII Maximum Daily Quantity, Excess Quantities and Fuel of this Statement. 2.12 "Excess Quantities" has the meaning ascribed in Article VII Maximum Daily Quantity, Excess Quantities and Fuel of this Statement. 2.13 "FERC" has the meaning set forth in Article I Introduction of this Statement, and will include any successor regulatory authority having or asserting jurisdiction to regulate matters that are the subject of this Statement. 2.14 "Firm Basis" means that, with respect to any Transportation Service, Shipper will deliver Gas to Transporter and Transporter will receive at the Receipt Point(s) and transport an Equivalent Quantity to the Delivery Point(s) without interruption, suspension or curtailment. 2.15 "Firm Transportation Service" means transportation service that is provided to Shippers on a Firm Basis. 2.16 "Fixed Downstream Fuel" has the meaning ascribed in Article VII Maximum Daily Quantity, Excess Quantities and Fuel of this Statement. 2.17 "Force Majeure" has the meaning ascribed in Article XIX Force Majeure of this Statement. 2.18 "Fuel" means the quantity of Gas that Transporter utilizes for fuel and loss, if any, associated with the compression and metering, in providing Transportation Service. 2.19 "Gas" means natural gas as produced in its natural state whether or not transported, stored or processed before Transporter or Shipper receives it under the Agreement, natural gas that has been previously liquefied and restored to its gaseous state before such receipt, and gas synthesized or manufactured from oil, naphtha, coal or any other material, that meets the quality standards contained in this Statement. 2.20 "Gas Daily Average Price" means the price published in Platts' Gas Daily Price Guide(r) (as published by S&P Global) under the heading Daily Midpoint Averages for "East Texas" for "Houston Ship Channel" for such applicable Month. Should Platts' GAS DAILY PRICE GUIDE(r) and/or the subject index cease to be published or is not reported for such Month, Transporter may, utilizing commercially reasonable principles, designate a replacement index or other pricing methodology. If Transporter discontinues its subscription to Platts' GAS DAILY PRICE GUIDE(r), the Parties agree to substitute comparable industry recognized gas pricing indices for purposes of the Agreement. Transporter shall update this Statement within sixty (60) days of designating an alternative index or pricing methodology. 2.21 "Heating Value" means gross heating value and is the number of Btu of energy transferred as heat per Cubic Foot of Gas from the complete, ideal combustion of the Gas with oxygen (from air), at Standard Temperature and Standard Pressure, in which all water formed by the reaction condenses to liquid. The Btu value will be determined utilizing the complete actual composition of the Gas delivered, but if the Gas as delivered contains seven (7) pounds or less of water vapor per one million (1,000,000) Cubic Feet, the Gas will be assumed to have zero (0) pounds of water per one million (1,000,000) Cubic Feet (dry Gas). 2.22 "Imbalance" has the meaning ascribed in Article IX Balancing of this Statement. 2.23 "Interruptible Basis" means Transportation Service that is subject to interruption at any time by Transporter, without liability as set forth in the Agreement. 2.24 "Interruptible Transportation Service" means Transportation Service provided to Shippers on an Interruptible Basis. 2.25 "Mainline System" has the meaning ascribed in the Recitals of the Agreement. 2.26 "Maximum Daily Quantity" or "MDQ" means the maximum quantity of Gas which Transporter is willing to receive for transport during one Day as specified in the Agreement. MDQ includes Estimated Mainline Fuel plus Fixed Downstream Fuel, as applicable. 2.27 "Mcf" means one thousand (1,000) Cubic Feet of Gas. 2.28 "MMBtu" means one million (1,000,000) Btu. 2.29 "Month" means a period beginning on the first (1st) Day of a calendar month and extending until the first (1st) Day of the following calendar month. 2.30 "NGPA" has the meaning ascribed in Article I Introduction of this Statement. 2.31 "Party" means either Transporter or Shipper, and the term "Parties," means both Transporter and Shipper. 2.32 "Pipeline System" has the meaning ascribed in the Recitals of the Agreement. 2.33 "PSIA" means pounds per square inch absolute. 2.34 "Receipt Point(s)" means the point(s) at which Gas is received by Transporter from Shipper. 2.35 "Section 311" has the meaning ascribed in Article I Introduction of this Statement. 2.36 "Section 311 Transportation Service" means Transportation Service that Transporter provides for Shipper pursuant to NGPA Section 311. 2.37 "Shipper" means the Party that has executed a Transportation Agreement with Transporter. 2.38 "Standard Pressure" means fourteen and seventy-three hundredths (14.73) pounds per square inch absolute. 2.39 "Standard Temperature" means sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60 F.). 2.40 "Taxes" means any tax (other than income, ad valorem tax, or excess profit taxes), license, fee or charge now or hereafter levied, assessed or made by a governmental authority on the act, right or privilege of receiving, storing, handling or delivering Gas which is measured by the volume, value, carbon content or sales price of the Gas or the gross receipts for providing Transportation Service. 2.41 "Tier" means either Tier 1 Capacity, Tier 2 Capacity, or Tier 3 Capacity. 2.42 "Tier 1 Capacity" means the initial design capacity of the Pipeline System of 2,000,000 MMBtu per day. 2.43 "Tier 1 Shipper" means any Shipper who entered into a Transportation Agreement for Tier 1 Capacity. 2.44 "Tier 2 Capacity" means the 100,000 MMBtu per day expansion created by adding additional compression to the initial design capacity of the Pipeline System. 2.45 "Tier 2 Shipper" means any Shipper who entered into a Transportation Agreement for Tier 2 Capacity. 2.46 "Tier 3 Capacity" means the 550,000 MMBtu per day expansion created by adding additional compression to the expanded capacity of the Pipeline System. 2.47 "Tier 3 Shipper" means any Shipper who entered into a Transportation Agreement for Tier 3 Capacity. 2.48 "Transportation Agreement" or "the Agreement" means the executed agreement between Transporter and Shipper providing for Transportation Service by Transporter. 2.49 "Transportation Service" means any transportation services provided by Transporter for Shipper at the Receipt and Delivery Point(s) pursuant to this Statement. 2.50 "Transporter" has the meaning ascribed in Article I Introduction of this Statement. 2.51 "Year" means a period of 365 consecutive Days, but any such period which contains the date of February 29 will consist of 366 consecutive Days. Article III. Transportation Services 3.1 Firm Transportation Service - Subject to the terms of this Statement and the applicable Transportation Agreement, Transporter will provide Firm Transportation Service on its Pipeline System for Shipper. 3.2 Interruptible Transportation Service - Subject to the terms of this Statement and the applicable Transportation Agreement, Transporter will provide Interruptible Transportation Service on its Pipeline System for Shipper on an as-available, Interruptible Basis. For service provided on an Interruptible Basis, Transporter will not be obligated to receive, transport, or re-deliver any minimum quantity of Gas. Transporter and Shipper may mutually agree upon a discounted rate that varies from the maximum rate established. (i) Interruptible Transportation Service will be provided when, and to the extent that, Transporter determines that interruptible capacity is available. (ii) Either Party, in its discretion, may interrupt, suspend or curtail the receipt or delivery of Gas at any time and from time to time with no liability of any kind or character to the other Party. 3.3 In addition to Section 311 Transportation Service, Transporter performs intrastate transportation services that are subject to the exclusive jurisdiction of the Texas Railroad Commission and that are exempt from FERC's regulation. To provide Shipper with flexibility to access intrastate and/or interstate markets, Shipper may contract for both intrastate and Section 311 Transportation Service on mutually agreeable terms, and Transporter will, at Shipper's option, administer Shipper's intrastate and Section 311 contracts on an integrated basis such that Shipper's combined usage under the intrastate and Section 311 agreements cannot exceed the MDQ indicated per Section 2.2 of Shipper's Transportation Agreement; provided, however, that Transporter's provision of Section 311 Transportation Service, without undue discrimination, shall not be conditioned on Shipper's subscription to intrastate capacity. The description of available intrastate services contained herein is provided for informational purposes only and shall not be construed to make such intrastate services subject to FERC regulation. Article IV. Eligibility of Shipper 4.1 In order to be eligible for Transportation Service, Shipper must represent and warrant to Transporter that the requested Transportation Service complies with the requirements of Section 311. 4.2 If, subsequent to commencement of the Transportation Service, Transporter in its reasonable discretion has reason to question the validity of Shipper's warranty set forth in the Performance of Transportation Service provision of the Agreement, Transporter may refuse to accept Shipper's tendered deliveries and may continue refusal until Shipper satisfies Transporter, in its reasonable discretion, of such representation and warranty. 4.3 In accordance with the Creditworthiness provision of this Statement and before Transportation Service begins, Transporter may require Shipper to supply Transporter with credit information including bank references, financial statements and names of persons with whom Shipper has recently transacted business in order that Transporter may make reasonable inquiry into Shipper's creditworthiness and obtain adequate assurance of Shipper's solvency and ability to perform. If Transporter determines that Shipper's creditworthiness is inadequate, Transporter will not be required to provide Transportation Service. Article V. Requests for Transportation Service 5.1 In order to enter into a Transportation Agreement, Shipper shall request Transportation Service in writing. Shipper must execute a Transportation Agreement prior to receiving Transportation Service. 5.2 Each request for Transportation Service will include the following information: (a) Shipper - the exact legal name and type of entity; mailing and street address; and the name, address and telephone number of primary contact for Shipper regarding the transportation arrangement. (b) The requested MDQ (stated in MMBtu/Day). (c) Term of Service: (i) the date Transportation Service is requested to commence; (ii) the date Transportation Service is requested to terminate. (d) Receipt and Delivery Point(s) - The Receipt and Delivery Point(s) for all Gas tendered to Transporter for transportation under the Transportation Agreement. (e) Eligibility - Information sufficient to satisfy the warranty requirements of Section 4.1. Article VI. Availability of Service 6.1 Transporter will provide Transportation Service for qualified Shippers pursuant to Section 311(a)(2), without undue discrimination or preference within the meaning of Sections 284.8(b)(1) and 284.9(b)(1) of the FERC's regulations, subject to (i) this Statement, (ii) all applicable legal and regulatory requirements and (iii) the terms and provisions contained in Transportation Agreements entered into between Transporter and qualified Shippers. 6.2 Interruptible Transportation Service will be subject to the availability of capacity in the Pipeline System not utilized on a Firm Basis. Article VII. Maximum Daily Quantity, Excess Quantities and Fuel 7.1 The Maximum Daily Quantity is as set forth in the Transportation Agreement. If Gas is received at any Receipt Point or redelivered at any Delivery Point in a commingled stream, Transporter will have the right to allocate that portion of the commingled stream for Shipper's account attributable to the Transportation Service provided under the Agreement. 7.2 If Shipper has quantities of Gas available on any Day for delivery to Transporter in excess of the MDQ ("Excess Quantities"), Shipper may tender such Excess Quantities for delivery to Transporter, and Transporter may in each such instance, accept or refuse delivery of all or any part of such Excess Quantities. Any Excess Quantities so accepted by Transporter will be transported on an Interruptible Basis and subject to all of the terms and provisions of the Transportation Agreement. 7.3 Transporter shall make a fair and equitable allocation, within each Tier, among shippers utilizing Tier 1 Capacity, Tier 2 Capacity, and Tier 3 Capacity of the actual amount of Fuel expended, consumed, lost or otherwise unaccounted for in providing Transportation Service on the Mainline System (the "Estimated Mainline Fuel"). Transporter shall adjust the Estimated Mainline Fuel for Tier 1 Shippers, Tier 2 Shippers, and Tier 3 Shippers at least every six (6) Months, within each Tier, based on the average actual amount of Fuel expended, consumed, lost or otherwise unaccounted for in providing Transportation Service on the Mainline System for the six (6) Month period ending two (2) Months before such adjustment date. Transporter shall notify Shipper of such adjusted Estimated Mainline Fuel no less than five (5) Days prior to the effective date thereof. Notwithstanding the foregoing, (i) Tier 1 Shipper's Estimated Mainline Fuel shall not exceed 2.3% of Tier 1 Shipper's nominated and confirmed quantities for such Month, (ii) Tier 2 Shipper's Estimated Mainline Fuel shall not exceed 4.0% of Tier 2 Shipper's nominated and confirmed quantities for such Month, and (iii) Tier 3 Shipper's Estimated Mainline Fuel shall not exceed 4.5% of Tier 3 Shipper's nominated and confirmed quantities for such Month. 7.4 In addition to the Estimated Mainline Fuel, to the extent a Tier 1 Shipper or Tier 2 Shipper utilizes Delivery Points on the Downstream System, each such Tier 1 Shipper and Tier 2 Shipper shall also be responsible for a fixed amount of 0.30% of Tier 1 Shipper's or Tier 2 Shipper's, as applicable, nominated and confirmed quantity of Gas for such Month (measured in MMBtu) for Tier 1 Shipper's or Tier 2 Shipper's, as applicable, Fuel expended, consumed, lost or otherwise unaccounted for in providing Transportation Service on the Downstream System ("Fixed Downstream Fuel"). The Fixed Downstream Fuel represents Transporter's fuel commitments to third party pipelines from which Transporter leases capacity for Tier 1 Shipper and Tier 2 Shipper that comprises part of the Pipeline System. 7.5 For each Tier, Shipper shall have the right to deliver to the Receipt Point(s) each Day an amount of Gas equal to the Equivalent Quantity of Gas plus Estimated Mainline Fuel and Fixed Downstream Fuel, as applicable. For each Tier, Transporter shall retain from Shipper an amount of Gas equal to the Estimated Mainline Fuel plus Fixed Downstream Fuel, as applicable, and shall deliver to Shipper at the Delivery Point(s) each Day an Equivalent Quantity. Article VIII. Allocation Statements During the periods Transporter receives Gas for Shipper and other third parties at any third party-allocated Receipt Point under the terms of the Agreement at which no operational balancing agreement is in effect, Shipper and Transporter shall use commercially reasonable efforts to cause the operator of such Receipt Point or its designee to furnish to Transporter, prior to flow during the relevant Month, a pre-determined allocation method setting forth (on a daily basis) the allocation of the total quantity of Gas to be received by Transporter at each Receipt Point during such Month. Shipper will be bound by, and Transporter will be entitled to rely conclusively on, such pre-determined allocation method. For third party-measured Receipt Point(s), Shipper will furnish or cause to be furnished a full tabulation of actual measured quantities of Gas received by the fifth (5th) Day of the Month following the Month of receipt.
Article IX. Balancing It is recognized that, because of dispatching and other operational variations, it may be physically impossible or operationally impractical for Transporter to redeliver to Shipper precisely Equivalent Quantities for any given Month. Therefore, any difference between the Equivalent Quantity and the actual quantity of Gas redelivered under the Agreement in any one (1) Month as calculated on an MMBtu basis ("Imbalance") will be computed and cashed out as provided below. Any positive difference between the Equivalent Quantity for any Month hereunder and actual redeliveries for any Month will be purchased by Transporter from Shipper at a price equal to ninety-five percent (95%) of the Gas Daily Average Price for the Month upon which such Imbalance occurred. Any negative difference between the Equivalent Quantity for any Month hereunder and actual redeliveries in such Month will be sold by Transporter to Shipper at a price equal to one hundred five percent (105%) of the Gas Daily Average Price for the Month on which such Imbalance occurred. Transporter will provide Shipper with a Monthly imbalance statement for each Month, setting forth any Monthly Imbalance and the basis thereof, expressed in MMBtu. Such statement will also set forth the price relevant to the Monthly cashout of all such imbalances.
Article X. Nominations and Dispatching 10.1 All nominations for Transportation Service will be submitted by Shipper at least monthly, but as frequently as daily if desired, through Transporter's DART system, through written nomination forms, or through such other electronic or written means as Transporter will specify, in accordance with Transporter's standard nomination procedures, as amended from time to time. Shipper will be bound by and Transporter may rely conclusively on Shipper's nominated quantities as confirmed by Transporter. Any variance from the nominated quantities must be submitted in writing or through such electronic means as Shipper and Transporter agree. Transporter will not be obligated to accept and/or confirm nominations for any Day for receipt or delivery of Gas at any point for which nominations in the aggregate are less than the minimum or greater than any maximum quantities set forth in the Agreement. Transporter reserves the right to amend its nomination procedures from time to time, as approved by FERC for NGPA Section 311(a)(2) service. 10.2 Each Agreement shall designate Shipper's primary receipt point(s), primary delivery point(s), secondary receipt point(s), and/or secondary delivery point(s). Nominations at secondary receipt point(s) or secondary delivery point(s) will be accepted up to the applicable point MDQ set forth in the Agreement, subject to curtailment with other shippers' secondary receipt point or secondary delivery point nominations at such point(s) on a pro rata basis based on the applicable MDQ, and subject to nominations at primary receipt point(s) or primary delivery point(s), as applicable. Once nominated and confirmed, service at secondary receipt points, secondary delivery points, primary receipt points, and primary delivery points will be curtailed or interrupted on a pro rata basis consistent with Article XII and Article VII. Article XI. Hourly Limits Transporter will not be obligated, during any hour, to receive a total quantity of Gas at any Receipt Point or to deliver a total quantity of Gas at any Delivery Point in excess of one twenty-fourth (1/24) of Shipper's MDQ for firm service at such Receipt or Delivery Point, and Transporter may impose such restriction whenever such restriction is necessary in order to meet its overall pipeline receipt and/or delivery obligations. However, if Shipper's load pattern temporarily requires receipts at any Receipt Point or deliveries at any Delivery Point in excess of such restriction, Transporter will, on request of Shipper, use reasonable efforts to accommodate such load pattern, and will consult with Shipper in an effort to generally accommodate load variation to the extent feasible and compatible with the needs of shippers as a group. If Shipper fails to restrict its hourly takes as specified herein after request by Transporter, Transporter may install and operate a load-limiting device at any Receipt or Delivery Point where such failure has occurred, and Shipper will fully cooperate in such installation. Shipper will reimburse Transporter for the reasonable cost of the load-limiting device to the extent installed due to Shipper's failure, including the cost of installation, within thirty (30) Days of its receipt of the bill. Transporter may, in regard to Interruptible Basis transportation quantities, impose any limitations that it deems reasonable.
Article XII. Priority of Service 12.1 If, for whatever reason, Transporter is unable to transport all quantities nominated by Shipper under the Transportation Agreement, then Transporter will interrupt Transportation Service in accordance with the following schedule of priorities, beginning with the first Transportation Service to be interrupted and continuing in order as necessary to the last Transportation Service to be interrupted: (a) Interruptible Transportation Service (b) Firm Transportation Service Within priority (a) above, interruption will be administered on the basis of price, with the Shipper paying the maximum rate receiving the highest priority. All remaining capacity shall be allocated such that the Shipper paying the next highest rate per MMBtu will receive the next highest priority. If two or more Interruptible Transportation Service shippers are paying the same rate for Section 311 Transportation Service, interruption will be administered on a pro rata basis based upon each Shipper's nomination. Within (b) above, capacity transport will be allocated pro rata based on each shipper's MDQ as applicable so that each shipper incurs an equal percentage reduction of its transportation rights.
Article XIII. Operating Conditions 13.1 In carrying out its Day-to-Day operations, Transporter, in its reasonable discretion, will determine the manner in which the Pipeline System will be utilized and which Transportation Service or requested Transportation Service will be provided. 13.2 Transporter will not be required to provide Transportation Service if: (a) providing it would cause Transporter to have insufficient capacity or operational capability to meet its existing contractual obligations; or (b) providing it would require Transporter to purchase or increase purchases of Gas; or (c) providing it would, in Transporter's reasonable judgment, be detrimental to Transporter's system operations; or (d) all facilities necessary to effectuate the Transportation Service are not in existence when the request for Transportation Service is made. 13.3 Unless otherwise agreed in writing, Transporter will be under no obligation to construct pipeline, compression or any other facilities for the receipt or redelivery of Gas under the Transportation Agreement. 13.4 Transporter's maximum obligation and minimum obligation to accept and redeliver Gas will be specified in the Transportation Agreement. 13.5 Transporter will not be required to perform Transportation Service on behalf of Shipper if Shipper is in breach of this Statement or the Transportation Agreement. Article XIV. Method of Measurement and Measurement Equipment 14.1 Assumed Atmospheric Pressure - The average atmospheric pressure will be assumed to be fourteen and seven tenths pounds per square inch absolute (14.7 PSIA). Where site conditions vary from this, at Transporter's option, the actual atmospheric pressure will be determined within one tenth (0.1) pound and used based on actual elevation or location of the Receipt or Delivery Point(s). 14.2 Unit of Volume - The unit of volume for measurement of Gas for all purposes will be one (1) Cubic Foot of Gas at Standard Temperature and Standard Pressure. All measurement equipment, constants, observations, records and procedures involved in the determination and/or verification of the quantity and other quality of Gas delivered under the Agreement will be in accordance with the latest edition and revisions of the standards listed below, each as amended from time to time. Neither Transporter nor Shipper will be required to replace or make any alterations to its previously installed measurement equipment as a result of amendments, revisions or modifications of the standards cited in this paragraph unless Transporter and Shipper agree to such replacement or alteration. (a) A.G.A. Report No. 3, Part 2, "Orifice Metering of Natural Gas and Other Related Hydrocarbon Fluids, Specifications and Installation Requirements", Fifth Edition, revised in March 2016 (Orifice Meter Tubes and Plates) (b) A.G.A. Report No. 3, Part 3, "Orifice Metering of Natural Gas and Other Related Hydrocarbon Fluids, Natural Gas Applications", Fourth Edition, revised in November 2013, (Orifice Meter Volume Calculations) (c) A.G.A. Report No. 7, "Measurement of Natural Gas by Turbine Meters", Second Revision, revised in February 2006. (Turbine Meter Tubes and Volume Calculations for all linear type meters (Turbine, Ultrasonic, Rotary, Diaphragm)) (d) A.G.A. Report No. 8, "Compressibility Factors of Natural Gas and Other Related Hydrocarbon Gases", Second Edition, revised in August 1994 (e) A.G.A. Report No. 9, "Measurement of Gas by Multipath Ultrasonic Meters", Second Edition, revised in April 2007 (Ultrasonic Meters and Tubes) (f) A.G.A. Report No. 11, "Measurement of Natural Gas by Coriolis Meter", First Edition, 2003 (Coriolis Meters) (g) GPA Standard 2145-16, "Table of Physical Constants for Hydrocarbons and Other Compounds of Interest to the Natural Gas Industry", revised in 2003 (constants for calculation of Heating Value and specific gravity, all meters) (h) GPA Standard 2166-05, "Obtaining Natural Gas Samples for Analysis by Gas Chromatography", revised in 2005 (i) GPA Standard 2172-09, "Calculation of Gross Heating Value, Relative Density and Compressibility Factor for Natural Gas Mixtures from Compositional Analysis", revised in 2009 (Calculation of Heating Value and Relative Density [Specific Gravity] for all meters) (j) GPA Standard 2261-00, "Analysis for Natural Gas and Similar Gaseous Mixtures by Gas Chromatography", revised in 2000 (k) API 14.1, "Collecting and Handling of Natural Gas Samples for Custody Transfer", Sixth Edition, revised in February 2006 (l) API 21.1, "Flow Measurement Using Electronic Metering Systems Section 1: Electronic Gas Measurement", September 1993 (all EFM systems) 14.3 Basis - The measurement of Gas will be corrected for deviation from Boyle's Law at the pressures and temperatures under which Gas is measured under the Agreement by use of the AGA Report No. 8 as referenced in the AGA Reports Nos. 3 and 9. 14.4 Determination of Gas Quality (Gas composition, Heating Value and specific gravity) - The Gas quality (including Gas composition, Heating Value and specific gravity) flowing through the meter(s) will be determined at the metering point(s) or at a mutually agreeable point where the flowing Gas is from the same source and there is no significant difference in the Gas quality. (a) At the option of the measuring Party, the Gas quality may be determined by an online chromatograph, a portable chromatograph, a continuous Gas sampler or by taking spot Gas samples. If samples are taken, the samples will be analyzed on a chromatograph by the measuring Party or by an independent laboratory. (b) Values for hydrocarbon components, carbon dioxide, nitrogen, Heating Value and specific gravity will all be determined from the same Gas analysis (or the average of values from Gas analysis over the same time period) and used for volume and energy computation starting at the same time. Other components (including water vapor, hydrogen sulfide, total sulfur, mercaptans, oxygen, and hydrogen) may be determined from separate samples or tests and taken at the same time. (c) If the water vapor content of the Gas is less than seven (7) pounds of water vapor per million (1,000,000) Cubic Feet of Gas, the Gas will be assumed to be dry for calculation of Heating Value. (d) The most recent Gas quality values available will be considered to be the Gas quality of the Gas flowing at the metering point and will be used for volume and energy computation from the time the results are available until new Gas quality values are available. (e) If Electronic Flow Measurement is used, then: (i) If an online chromatograph at the metering point is used, new Gas quality values will be used when they are available. (ii) If the online chromatograph is located at a point other than the metering point and a data communication system is installed, the EFM will be updated with the most recent Gas quality values as often as practical but at least once per Day. (iii) If a data communication system is not installed and the EFM system is updated manually, the average Gas quality values from the online chromatograph will be computed at least once per Month and entered into the EFM. The average Gas quality values will be computed for the time period since the previous averages were computed but not for a period of more than one (1) Month. (iv) If a portable chromatograph, a continuous sample, or a spot sample is used, the new Gas quality values will be entered into the EFM when the results are available. (f) Heating Value will be determined to the nearest one tenth (0.1) Btu. Specific gravity will be determined to the nearest one ten thousandth (0.0001). Each component of the Gas composition will be determined to the nearest one ten thousandth (0.0001) mole percent. If an EFM system is used, higher precision may be used for calculations. 14.5 Determination of Flowing Temperature - The temperature of the Gas flowing through the meter or meters will be determined by the continuous use of a recording thermometer or temperature transmitters installed so that they will properly record the temperature of the Gas flowing through the meter or meters. 14.6 Determination of Specific Gravity - The specific gravity of the Gas flowing through the meter or meters may be determined by the use of a chromatograph or by analysis of Gas collected in spot and continuous samplers. Specific gravity will be updated whenever the Heating Value of the Gas is updated. All specific gravity determinations made with a chromatograph will use physical Gas constants for Gas compounds as outlined in the GPA Std 2145-16 Rev 1 Table of Physical Constants of Paraffin Hydrocarbons and other Components of Natural Gas with any subsequent amendments or revisions to such report to which the Parties agree. Specific gravity will be determined to the nearest ten thousandth (0.0001). 14.7 Equipment - All facilities necessary to measure the Gas at the Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) will have been installed and will be in operation as of Service Commencement Date. Any necessary metering facilities which are installed subsequent to such date will be installed, paid for, owned, operated, and maintained as mutually agreeable between Shipper and Transporter. Any new measurement and appurtenant facilities required at the Receipt and Delivery Point(s) will be installed, owned, operated, and maintained by Transporter or Transporter's designee. Title to such facilities will be and remain in Transporter or Transporter's designee.
As specified by Transporter, all measuring stations it owns or operates at the Receipt Point(s) or Delivery Point(s), or which are owned and operated by Transporter's designee, will be equipped with orifice, turbine, ultrasonic or other types of meter(s) of standard make and design commonly accepted in the natural gas industry in order to accurately measure the Gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper under the Agreement. At Transporter's election, an EFM, transducers and other associated sensing devices may be installed to accurately measure the Gas at the metering points it owns or operates in accordance with A.G.A. Report Nos. 3, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, and 11, as appropriate. If an EFM and associated devices are installed, Gas quality values will be entered either manually or as real time data if such data is available. All Gas quality values used in super compressibility correction determinations will be entered as real time data if such data is available or, if the Gas quality source is a composite or spot sample, the values will be entered manually each time they are determined at intervals mutually agreed upon, but at least once every six (6) Months.
14.8 Calibration and Tests of Meters - If used, chromatographs will be calibrated by the measuring Party using a certified calibration Gas standard, as frequently as required by applicable law, but at least Daily. All other measuring equipment will be calibrated and adjusted as necessary by the measuring Party based on the following: (a) Monthly if average volume is greater than or equal to 25,000 MMBtu/Day; (b) bi-Monthly if average volume is between 5,000 MMBtu/Day and 25,000 MMBtu/Day; (c) quarterly if average volume is between 2,000 MMBtu/Day and 5,000 MMBtu/Day; (d) semiannually if average volume is less than or equal to 2,000 MMBtu/Day; or (e) as frequently as deemed necessary by the measuring Party but not more than once each Month. The other Party may, at its option, be present for such calibration and adjustment. The measuring Party will give the other Party notice of the time of all tests sufficiently in advance of conducting same so that both Parties may conveniently have their representatives present. Following any test, any measuring equipment found to be inaccurate to any degree will be adjusted immediately to measure accurately. Each Party will have the right, at any time, to challenge the accuracy of any measuring equipment used and may request additional tests. If, upon testing, the challenged equipment is found to be in error, then it will be repaired and calibrated. The cost of any such special testing, repair and calibration will be borne by the Party requiring the special test if the percentage of inaccuracy is found to be one percent (1%) or less; otherwise, the cost will be borne by the Party operating the challenged measuring equipment.
14.9 Access to Meters, Measurement Equipment and Records - The other Party will have access at all reasonable times to the measuring equipment and all other instruments used by the measuring Party in determining the measurement and quality of the Gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper, but the reading, calibrating, and adjusting thereof will be done only by employees, agents or representatives of the measuring Party. The measurement data and records will be kept on file by the measuring Party for a period of one (1) Year for Transporter's and Shipper's mutual use. Upon request, the measuring Party will submit to the other Party measurement data and records from such equipment, subject to return by that Party within thirty (30) Days after receipt. 14.10 Correction of Metering Errors - If, upon any test, the measuring equipment in the aggregate is found to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1%), registration thereof and any payments based upon such registration will be corrected at the rate of such inaccuracy for any period of inaccuracy which is definitely known or agreed upon, but if such period is not definitely known or agreed upon, then such registration and payment will be corrected for a period extending back one-half (l/2) of the time elapsed since the date of the prior calibration (but with such corrected period not to exceed ninety (90) Days). 14.11 Failure of Meters - If, for any reason, the measuring equipment is out of service or out of repair so that the quantity of Gas delivered through such measuring equipment cannot be ascertained or computed from the readings thereof, the quantity of Gas delivered during the period such equipment is out of service or out of repair will be estimated upon the basis of the best available data, using the first of the following methods which is feasible: (a) By using the registration of any duplicate measuring equipment installed by the measuring Party, if installed and registering correctly; (b) By correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, test or mathematical calculation; (c) By using the registration of any check measuring equipment of the other Party, if installed and registering accurately; or (d) By estimating the quantity of deliveries by using the Gas quantities delivered to Transporter or Shipper, as applicable, under similar conditions during preceding periods when the measuring equipment was registering accurately. 14.12 Check Measuring Equipment - Each Party may install, maintain and operate at its own expense such check measuring equipment as desired; provided, however, that such equipment will be installed so as not to interfere with the operation of any other measuring equipment. Each Party will have access to the check meter(s) installed by the other Party at all reasonable times, but the reading, calibration and adjusting thereof will be done only by the employees or agents of the operating Party. 14.13 New Measurement Techniques - If, at any time during the term of the Agreement, a new method or technique is developed with respect to Gas measurement or the determination of the factors used in Gas measurement, such new method or technique may be substituted for the method set forth in this Article when the Parties agree that employing such new method or technique is advisable. Article XV. Quality 15.1 Quality Specifications - The Gas received by Transporter from Shipper at the Receipt Point(s) and delivered by Transporter to Shipper at the Delivery Point(s) under the terms of the Agreement will conform on a specification-by-specification basis to the more stringent of the following specifications and the then-applicable quality specifications of the downstream pipelines: (a) The Gas will be Commercially Free of water and other objectionable liquids at the temperature and pressure at which the Gas is delivered to Transporter and the Gas will not contain any hydrocarbons which might condense to free liquids in the pipeline under normal pipeline conditions and will in no event contain water vapor in excess of seven (7) pounds per one million (1,000,000) Cubic Feet of Gas, measured at Standard Temperature and Standard Pressure. (b) The Gas will not contain more than twenty-five hundredths (0.25) of one grain of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) Cubic Feet of Gas as determined by quantitative methods in general use in the natural gas industry and as mutually acceptable to the Parties. (c) The Gas will not contain more than one half (0.50) of one grain of total sulfur per one hundred (100) Cubic Feet of Gas as determined by quantitative methods in general use in the natural gas industry and as mutually acceptable to the Parties. (d) The Gas will not contain more than three tenths (0.3) of one grain of mercaptans per one hundred (100) Cubic Feet of Gas as determined by quantitative methods in general use in the natural gas industry and as mutually acceptable to the Parties. (e) The Gas will not contain in excess of: (i) Two (2) mole percent of carbon dioxide (CO2); (ii) Ten parts per million (10 ppm) by volume of oxygen (O2); (iii) Three (3) mole percent of nitrogen (N2); (iv) Two-tenths (0.2) gallon per Mcf of isopentane (C5+) and heavier hydrocarbons; and (v) In the aggregate, three (3) mole percent of non-hydrocarbons. (f) Any Gas in excess of ten parts per million (10 ppm), but not in excess of one hundred parts per million (100 ppm), by volume of oxygen (O2), will be accepted so long as blended gas of all receipt volumes received by Transporter will be accepted by downstream pipelines. (g) The Gas will contain no carbon monoxide, halogens or unsaturated hydrocarbons and not more than four hundred parts per million (400 ppm) of hydrogen. (h) The Gas will have a temperature of not more than one hundred twenty degrees Fahrenheit (120 F.) and not less than forty degrees Fahrenheit (40 F.). (i) The Gas will have a Btu value (higher heating value) of not greater than one thousand one hundred (1,100) Btu per Cubic Foot (Btu/cf) and not less than nine hundred seventy-five (975) Btu per Cubic Foot. (j) The Gas will have a hydrocarbon dew point of not more than twenty degrees Fahrenheit (20 F) at normal pipeline operating pressures; however should the Gas contain a hydrocarbon dew point greater than twenty degrees Fahrenheit (20 F), but less than or equal to forty degrees Fahrenheit (40 F), Transporter will accept such blended Gas provided that such blended Gas is accepted by downstream pipelines. (k) The Gas will be Commercially Free from odors, dirt, dust, gums, gum-forming constituents, iron oxide, iron sulfide, and any other objectionable liquid or solid matter which might interfere with the merchantability of the Gas stream, or cause interference with proper operation of the lines, meters, regulators, other appliances through which it may flow, or transportation to any downstream pipeline. (l) The Gas will be free of any and all corrosive materials that may, in Transporter's determination, be harmful to the facilities. 15.2 Failure to Meet Quality Specifications - If either Party determines the Gas delivered to it fails to meet the quality specifications prescribed above, such Party will have the right without notice to immediately terminate the receipt of any Gas failing to meet such quality specifications, but will as soon as practical notify in writing the other Party of such action and the basis thereof. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Transporter may continue to accept Gas that does not meet the foregoing quality specifications. In such an event Transporter may propose to Shipper a conditioning fee relevant to such Gas that fails to meet quality specifications. The amount of such proposed conditioning fee will be determined by Transporter utilizing a commercially reasonable methodology. Shipper will notify Transporter as soon as practicable regarding whether it agrees to pay such a conditioning fee hereunder. 15.3 SHIPPER SHALL INDEMNIFY, SAVE, DEFEND, AND HOLD HARMLESS TRANSPORTER AND ITS AFFILIATES, SUBSIDIARIES, AND PARENT, AND ITS AND THEIR RESPECTIVE EMPLOYEES, OFFICERS, DIRECTORS, SHAREHOLDERS, PARTNERS, MEMBERS, MANAGERS, AGENTS, REPRESENTATIVES, AND INSURERS FROM AND AGAINST ANY AND ALL LOSSES, COSTS, DAMAGES, LIABILITIES, CLAIMS, ACTIONS, SUITS, DEBTS, ACCOUNTS, AND EXPENSES (INCLUDING COURT COSTS AND REASONABLE ATTORNEYS' FEES) OF TRANSPORTER OF WHATSOEVER NATURE (INCLUDING COSTS OF CLEANING, REPAIRING, OR REPLACING THE AFFECTED PORTION OF TRANSPORTER'S PIPELINE SYSTEM), WHETHER ARISING OUT OF CONTRACT, TORT, OR STRICT LIABILITY, CAUSED BY, RESULTING FROM, OR ARISING OUT OF SHIPPER'S DELIVERY OF GAS WHICH FAILS TO MEET THE QUALITY SPECIFICATIONS OF THIS ARTICLE. Article XVI. Receipt and Delivery Pressure 16.1 All Gas delivered at the Receipt Point(s) will be delivered at pressures sufficient to enter Transporter's Pipeline System at the working pressures maintained by Transporter at the Receipt Point from time to time. Transporter will not be obligated to receive Gas at pressures exceeding the maximum allowable operating pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations. 16.2 All Gas redelivered at the Delivery Point(s) will be redelivered at the working pressures maintained by Transporter at the Delivery Point from time to time. Shipper will not be obligated to receive Gas at pressures exceeding the maximum allowable operating pressures downstream of the Delivery Point(s) prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations. Article XVII. Taxes and Fee Reimbursement Shipper will be responsible for Taxes and certain other fees as follows: (a) Tax Reimbursement - Shipper will reimburse Transporter for all Taxes which are levied upon and/or paid by Transporter with respect to the Transportation Service performed under the terms of the Agreement or in respect to Shipper's Gas while the Gas is in the possession of Transporter. Without limiting the foregoing, it is specifically agreed that Shipper will reimburse Transporter for any state utilities Taxes to which Transporter may be subject due to its receipt, transportation, handling, and/or delivery of Gas under the Agreement. (b) Reimbursement of Fees - Shipper will reimburse Transporter for any and all filing fees in connection with providing Transportation Service to Shipper under the Agreement that Transporter is required to pay by any governmental authority having or asserting jurisdiction. Article XVIII. Title, Possession & Responsibility 18.1 Title. Shipper represents and warrants to Transporter that Shipper has full and unqualified authority to deliver Gas to Transporter, and that Gas is free from any and all liens, charges, claims and encumbrances. Shipper will indemnify, defend, and save Transporter harmless from and against any and all regulatory proceedings, suits, actions, claims, demands, damages, costs, losses, penalties and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees) arising from or out of any breach of the foregoing representation and warranty. Title to Shipper's Gas in Transporter's Pipeline System will remain with Shipper or its designee at all times, except that title to those quantities of Gas tendered to Transporter for Estimated Mainline Fuel plus Fixed Downstream Fuel, if any, as provided in the Agreement, will pass to Transporter at the Receipt Point(s). 18.2 Possession and Responsibility. Shipper or its designee will be deemed in possession of and responsible for the Gas before Transporter receives it at the Receipt Point(s) and after Transporter redelivers the Gas to Shipper or its designee by Transporter at the Delivery Point(s). Transporter will have no responsibility with respect to the Gas before receipt from Shipper at the Receipt Point(s) or after delivery to Shipper at the Delivery Point(s). Transporter will be deemed in possession of and responsible for the Gas after receipt of the Gas at the Receipt Point(s) until the Gas is redelivered to Shipper at the Delivery Point(s). EACH PARTY AGREES TO RELEASE, DEFEND, PROTECT, INDEMNIFY, AND HOLD HARMLESS THE OTHER, ITS AFFILIATES, THEIR DIRECTORS, OFFICERS, AGENTS, CONTRACTORS, SUBCONTRACTORS, AND EMPLOYEES (COLLECTIVELY, "INDEMNITEES"), FROM EVERY KIND OR CHARACTER OF DAMAGES, LOSSES, LIABILITIES, EXPENSES, DEMANDS, CLAIMS, OR SUITS FOR DEATH OR INJURY TO PERSONS OR PROPERTY, INCLUDING ANY AND ALL COSTS AND FEES (ATTORNEYS, COURT, EXPERTS OR OTHERWISE) ARISING OUT OF ANY INVESTIGATION, LITIGATION OR SETTLEMENT OF ANY CLAIMS (COLLECTIVELY, "LOSSES"), ARISING FROM OR OCCURRING WHILE THE INDEMNIFYING PARTY IS DEEMED TO BE IN POSSESSION OF THE GAS, UNDER ANY LEGAL THEORY WHATSOEVER AND REGARDLESS OF WHETHER SUCH LOSSES MAY HAVE BEEN CAUSED IN PART BY ANY NEGLIGENT ACT OR OMISSION, EITHER ACTIVE OR PASSIVE, OR THE STRICT LIABILITY (STATUTORY OR OTHERWISE) OF ANY INDEMNITEES OR ANY THIRD PARTY, WHETHER SUCH ACT OR OMISSION CONSTITUTES SOLE, PARTIAL, OR CONCURRENT NEGLIGENCE OR IS THE SOLE PROXIMATE OR PRODUCING CAUSE OF THE LOSSES. Neither Transporter nor Shipper will be liable for the gross negligence or willful misconduct of the other Party. Article XIX. Force Majeure 19.1 If Force Majeure renders either Party unable (either in whole or in part) to carry out its obligations under the Agreement, other than its obligations to make payments due, then the obligations of the Party claiming Force Majeure will be suspended during the duration of any inability resulting from Force Majeure. A Party claiming Force Majeure will give notice and full particulars of such Force Majeure in writing to the other Party as soon as possible. A Party's obligations will be suspended as long as the Party is impacted by the Force Majeure (which may last longer than the cause of the Force Majeure) but for no longer period. Before either Party is entitled to suspend its performance, the Party is required to exercise reasonable diligence and incur reasonable cost to prevent or overcome the Force Majeure. 19.2 Force Majeure, as employed in this Statement, will include any and all of the following and any other causes, whether of the kind enumerated below or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the Party claiming suspension and which by the exercise of due diligence such Party is unable to prevent or overcome at reasonable cost and exercise of reasonable diligence: (a) events beyond the reasonable control of the Party claiming Force Majeure, including acts of God, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, acts of the public enemy, terrorism, sabotage, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, freezes, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, hurricanes, floods, high water, washouts or other natural disasters, threat of physical harm or damage resulting in the evacuation or shut down of facilities necessary for the production, delivery, receipt, transportation, or use of the Gas, arrests and restraints of governments and people, civil disturbances, or explosions; (b) breakage or accident to machinery, lines of pipe, or facilities in which the Gas is transported, processed, or used, which is not due to Transporter's failure to complete routine maintenance, testing and repairs; (c) the necessity of testing, or the necessity of repairs or alterations to wells, machinery, facilities (including processing, gathering, transportation, gasification and Gas manufacturing facilities) or lines of pipe through which the Gas is moved, which is not due to Transporter's failure to complete routine maintenance, testing and repairs; (d) partial or entire failure of wells, lines of pipe, or other facilities (including processing, gathering, transportation, gasification, and Gas manufacturing facilities) in which the Gas is used; (e) orders of any court or governmental authority or agency having or asserting jurisdiction, or the refusal or withdrawal of any necessary order, certificate or permit by any court or governmental authority or agency having or asserting jurisdiction, which are not reasonably foreseeable by the Party claiming suspension; (f) any acts or omissions (including failure to take, transport or deliver Gas) of a transporter of Gas to or for Transporter or Shipper; (g) in those instances where either Party is required to obtain servitudes, rights-of-way grants, permits, certificates, tariffs, or licenses to enable such Party to fulfill its obligations under this Statement or the Agreement, the inability of such Party to acquire or the delays on the part of such Party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such servitudes, rights-of-way grants, permits, certificates, tariffs, or licenses; including but not limited to the FERC determining that the service provided by this Statement and the Agreement constitutes interstate transportation of natural gas subject to the Natural Gas Act; (h) in those instances where either Party is required to furnish materials and supplies, or hire vendors or suppliers, for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permissions from any governmental agency to enable such Party to fulfill its obligations under the Agreement, the inability of such Party to acquire or the delays on the part of such Party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such materials and supplies, permits and permissions (including delays caused by third party vendors and suppliers); and (i) any other causes, whether of the kind enumerated above or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the Party claiming suspension and which by the exercise of due diligence such Party is unable to prevent or overcome at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence. 19.3 As used in the Agreement, the terms "reasonable control," "reasonable diligence" and "reasonable cost" will not require a Party to use extraordinary efforts or incur extraordinary costs to avoid or remedy the Force Majeure event or its effects. 19.4 Neither Party will be entitled to the benefit of Force Majeure to the extent performance is affected by any or all of the following circumstances, except when the enumerated circumstances themselves are caused by the event of Force Majeure: (a) the Party claiming excuse failed to remedy the condition and to resume the performance of such covenants or obligations with reasonable dispatch (which will not require the use of extraordinary efforts or payment of extraordinary costs); (b) economic hardship, to include, without limitation, Transporter's ability to sell Transportation Service at a higher or more advantageous fee than the fee provided in the Agreement, and Shipper's ability to buy Transportation Service at a lower or more advantageous fee than the fee provided in the Agreement; (c) the loss of Shipper's market(s) or Shipper's inability to use or resell Gas transported under the Agreement; or (d) the loss or failure of Shipper's Gas supply or depletion of reserves. 19.5 It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts will be entirely within the discretion of the Party having the difficulty and that the above requirement that any Force Majeure will be remedied with all reasonable dispatch will not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing person when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the Party having the difficulty. 19.6 Notwithstanding the foregoing, it is specifically understood and agreed by the Parties that Force Majeure will in no way terminate the Parties' obligations to balance volumes of Gas under the Agreement. Article XX. Invoicing and Accounting 20.1 Accounting Statements - Transporter will render to Shipper, on or before the fifteenth (l5th) Day of each Month an invoice setting forth, (i) with respect to all Gas received by Transporter during the preceding Month at the Receipt Point(s), the total quantity and the Heating Value of the Gas, (ii) with respect to all Gas redelivered to Shipper during the preceding Month at the Delivery Point(s), the total quantity and the Heating Value of the Gas, (iii) the charges due Transporter under the Agreement, including all exhibits thereto and, if applicable, (iv) all monthly imbalances and detailing the cash-out thereof. Transporter may initially bill on its best reasonably available estimates if all actual information is not available at the time the invoice is to be sent. Shipper agrees to make payment to Transporter by wire transfer or other electronic means, for all charges incurred during the preceding Month on the later of the twenty-fifth (25th) Day of each Month or within ten (10) Days after the date of the invoice, but if the twenty-fifth (25th) Day of Month is on a weekend or federal bank holiday, payment is due on the next Day that is not a federal bank holiday. If the invoice for any Month has a date subsequent to the fifteenth (15th) Day of the Month, then the time for payment will be extended for a period equal to the delay, unless Shipper is responsible for the delay. 20.2 Late Payment - If Shipper fails to pay any amount due Transporter when it is due, the unpaid balance will bear interest from the due date until the date paid at a rate equal to the applicable rate published by FERC in accordance with 18 C.F.R. 154.501(d) of FERC's regulations. If Shipper's failure to pay continues for thirty (30) Days, Transporter will, in addition to its other remedies, have the right to suspend services under and/or to terminate the Agreement without prior notice, without prejudice to any and all claims for damages or other rights or remedies available under this Statement, the Agreement or pursuant to law, and without liability of any kind or character to Shipper. 20.3 Errors and Disputes in Statements - If Transporter discovers an error in the amount billed in any invoice rendered by Transporter, the error will be adjusted within thirty (30) Days of the discovery of the error. If a dispute arises as to the amount payable in any invoice rendered, Shipper will nevertheless pay the total amount payable to Transporter under the invoice rendered pending resolution of the dispute. Shipper's payment will not be deemed to be a waiver by Shipper of the right to recoup any overpayment. Transporter will repay any overpayment together with interest calculated under the method set forth in Section 20.2 of this Statement. 20.4 Examination of Books and Records - Each Party will have the right at reasonable hours to examine the books and records of the other Party to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement, calculation or determination made pursuant to the provisions of the Agreement. If any such examination reveals, or if either Party discovers, any error in its own or the other Party's statements, calculations or determinations, then proper adjustment and correction of the error will be made as promptly as practicable. 20.5 Finality - All invoices and billings will be conclusively presumed final and accurate unless objected to in writing, with adequate explanation and/or documentation, within two (2) Years after the Month of Gas delivery pertaining to such invoice or billing. Article XXI. Creditworthiness 21.1 Throughout the term of the Agreement, upon request by Transporter, Shipper will provide Transporter with its, its parent entity's, or its guarantor's, as applicable, annual audited financial statements and quarterly unaudited financial statements prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles; provided, however, if such entity is required to make its annual audited and quarterly financial statements available to the public, then Transporter will use public sources to obtain the information. 21.2 If Transporter has reasonable grounds for insecurity regarding Shipper's performance (whether or not then due) of any obligation under this Statement or the Agreement, including but not limited to, the occurrence of a material change in the creditworthiness of Shipper or its guarantor, if applicable, then Transporter may demand Adequate Assurance of Performance (as defined below). If Shipper has not provided Adequate Assurance of Performance to Transporter within two (2) business Days of Shipper's, or its guarantor's, if applicable, receipt of such request, then Transporter will have the right to either (i) suspend performance for which it has not already received the agreed upon return consideration or (ii) terminate the Agreement upon written notice, in addition to all other remedies available to it under the Agreement. "Adequate Assurance of Performance" means sufficient security in the form, amount, for a term, and from an issuer, all as reasonably acceptable to Transporter, including, but not limited to (i) cash deposit (ii) payment with an accelerated due date or a more frequent basis than a monthly billing cycle, (iii) a standby irrevocable letter of credit, (iv) a prepayment, (v) a security interest in an asset acceptable to Transporter for an amount equal to at least three (3) months' demand charges under the Agreement, for a term reasonably acceptable to Transporter based upon the volumes flowed by Shipper under its Transportation Agreement in the immediately preceding three (3) months, or (vi) payment guaranty that satisfies at least two of the following: (A) rated at least Baa3 by Moody's Investor's Service, Inc. or its successor with stable outlook; (B) rated at least BBB- by Fitch Ratings Inc. or its successor with stable outlook; and (C) rated at least BBB- by Standard & Poor's or its successor with stable outlook, or (5) a security interest in an asset. Shipper hereby grants to Transporter a continuing first priority security interest in, lien on, and right of setoff against all Adequate Assurance of Performance in the form of cash transferred by Shipper to Transporter pursuant to this Article. Upon the return by Transporter to Shipper of such Adequate Assurance of Performance, the security interest and lien granted hereunder on that Adequate Assurance of Performance will be released automatically and, to the extent possible, without any further action by either party. 21.3 If Shipper or its guarantor, if applicable: (i) makes an assignment or any general arrangement for the benefit of creditors; (ii) files a petition or otherwise commences, authorizes, or acquiesces in the commencement of a proceeding or case under any bankruptcy or similar law for the protection of creditors or have such petition filed or proceeding commenced against it which is not dismissed within thirty (30) Days of being filed or commenced; (iii) otherwise becomes bankrupt or insolvent (however evidenced); (iv) becomes unable to pay its debts as they fall due; (v) has a receiver, provisional liquidator, conservator, custodian, trustee or other similar official appointed with respect to it or substantially all of its assets; (vi) fails to perform any material obligation to Transporter; (vii) fails to give Adequate Assurance of Performance as required under this Statement; or (viii) fails to pay any amount due Transporter on or before the second Business Day following written Notice that such payment is due, then Transporter will have the right, at its sole election, to immediately withhold and/or suspend service upon prior written notice and/or to terminate the Agreement, in addition to any and all other remedies available under this Statement and the Agreement. Article XXII. Laws and Regulations This Statement and the Agreement will be subject to all valid existing and future law, orders, rules, regulations or proclamations of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction or control over the Parties or the subject matter of this Statement and the Agreement. If any such governmental authority takes any action which is, with respect to or as a result of this Statement or the Agreement, designed to subject or otherwise subjects Transporter or any of its pipelines or related facilities to any greater or different regulation or jurisdiction than that existing on the date of this Statement or the Agreement (or thereafter as such regulation or jurisdiction may have changed and been accepted by the Party), then upon written notice to the other, Transporter may cancel and terminate this Agreement effective one (1) Day before the effective date of such governmental action without further obligation. Nothing contained in this Statement or the Agreement will be construed as a waiver of any right to question or contest any such law, order, decision, rule or regulation in any forum having jurisdiction in the premises or services set forth herein.
Transporter will file all necessary reports and/or notices required by any governmental authority, and Shipper will provide Transporter with any necessary compliance information required by Transporter in connection with preparing such reports. Article XXIII. Warranty Shipper warrants that neither it nor its designees will take any action(s) with respect to the Gas to be transported under the Agreement that would subject Transporter to the jurisdiction of FERC under the Natural Gas Act. If Transporter, FERC, or a government authority determines that the Agreement, Transporter, and/or Pipeline System are providing interstate transportation service subject to regulation under the Natural Gas Act, then the Parties will negotiate reasonable and valid provisions to restore the economic benefit of the Parties reflected in the Agreement; including, if feasible, execution of an applicable transportation agreement pursuant to an appropriate interstate gas pipeline tariff. Article XXIV. Odorization Shipper and Transporter agree that none of the Gas delivered by Transporter to or for the account of Shipper pursuant to the Agreement will be odorized. Any odorization that may be required by any applicable statute, order, rule or regulation at any location downstream of the Delivery Points will be the sole responsibility of Shipper or its designee. Shipper will indemnify and hold Transporter and its Affiliates harmless from any and all claims, demands, causes of action, losses, damages or injuries (including death) that may result from the operation and maintenance of odorization facilities or equipment at, near or downstream of the Delivery Points, or the lack thereof, or that result from the failure of Shipper to properly odorize Gas delivered by Transporter hereunder.
Article XXV. Governing Law THE AGREEMENT WILL BE INTERPRETED, CONSTRUED AND GOVERNED BY THE LAWS OF THE STATE OF TEXAS, EXCLUDING ANY CONFLICT OF LAW RULES WHICH WOULD REFER TO THE LAWS OF ANOTHER JURISDICTION. EXCLUSIVE VENUE FOR ANY ACTION BROUGHT HEREUPON WILL BE IN THE STATE OR FEDERAL COURTS LOCATED IN HOUSTON, HARRIS COUNTY, TEXAS. Reasonable attorneys' fees and costs may be awarded to the prevailing Party in connection with any action taken to enforce its rights under the Agreement.

Limitation of Liability NEITHER PARTY WILL BE LIABLE TO THE OTHER PARTY FOR LOSS OF PROFITS, SPECIAL, INDIRECT, INCIDENTAL, OR CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES ARISING OUT OF A BREACH OF THE AGREEMENT OR OBLIGATION UNDER THE AGREEMENT OR OUT OF WARRANTY, CONTRACT, TORT OR OTHERWISE. Modification Transporter reserves the right, at any time and from time to time, to modify or revise this Statement, in accordance with FERC requirements for NGPA Section 311(a)(2) service.

Severability If any portion of the Statement or the Agreement is found invalid or required to be modified as a matter of law in a duly authorized court or by a duly authorized governmental authority, then only that portion of this Statement or the Agreement will be invalid or modified. Assignment Transporter may assign or otherwise convey all or any portion of its rights, titles, or interests under the Agreement Shipper may assign or otherwise convey all or any portion of its rights, titles, or interests under the Agreement only after obtaining the prior written consent of Transporter which consent will not be unreasonably withheld or delayed; provided, however, that Shipper may, without consent, assign all or any portion of its rights, titles, and interests under the Agreement to an Affiliate. Article XXX.
